<br>
Lessee... a list of her capabilities:<br>
High school graduate.<br>
chef.<br>
upholsterer.<br>
painter (both house and art)<br>
interior designer<br>
landscaper/gardener.<br>
medic.<br>
seamstress.<br>
teacher.<br>
political activist.<br>
wallpaper hanger.<br>
accountant.<br>
writer.<br>
computer operator.<br>
office manager.<br>
I'd add mother, but that would be redundant. In short, she was a Renaissance Woman.<br>
She was married to the same man for 50 years. Bore 4 children and raised them to adulthood, and still gets quiet at certain times of the year mourning the loss of her 2nd child, in the womb.<br>
She made do with the income provided by her construction-working husband (read: not a hell of a lot most of the time.) When she was married, she could not cook or sew, period. By the time her youngest was born, she was a competent chef, and has never felt challenged by any recipe she's encountered. (except, I think, divinity...) She learned to sew to help provide her children with sufficient clothes of superior quality. The culmination of this, years later, was the wedding dress that was the (literal) envy of the town she made for her daughter. Oh, yes, and due to her and her husband's diligent efforts and instilled values, the daughter was able to legitimately wear white at her wedding.<br>
In order to provide a sufficiently clean environment for her family in the early days of her marriage, she learned to paint, wallpaper and decorate on a budget. (Later in life she would amuse herself by watching craft and design shows and chuckling at the &quot;new&quot; ideas she had done decades earlier.)<br>
She would also apply the home-remedy skills she learned in raising her own children to save the life of her infant grandson when he was dying of dehydration (sadly, his mother, her daughter-<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  in-law</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> was an avowed feminazi... )<br>
<br>
If you look on a voting chart for the 1980 election primary for the State of Iowa, you'll find a curious anomaly. You'll see districts which went for Bush surrounding a district which went for Reagan; her efforts. Later she would be informed by party higher ups that her district had been one of the ones the Reagan campaign had written-off. Her reward for this, other than the admiration of her husband, was a signed letter from President Reagan. <br>
After 40-odd years of marriage, of learning to do things she never dreamed of doing as a girl, her successful daughter (gasp) offered her employment as a secretary in her office; a job intended to be an excuse to provide medical benefits to her parents, and a retirement income, but require no real effort... supposedly. She instead became the office manager, with the responsibility of running the office, balancing the books, creating documents, and a host of other duties. For the first time in her life, she learned to operate a computer. Basically, her reformed daughter (now a feminazi herself, on her 2nd husband) worked her into the ground, while constantly reminding her how much of a burden she and her husband were, how incompetent and inadequate she was in all ways. Fortunately, her husband had not retired, so she had the option of quitting (actually she didn't; once her husband became aware of the abuse he put his foot down and wouldn't have let her go back had she wanted to.)<br>
Oddly, the entire staff viewed her differently, including the computer expert they brought in to revamp their entire system, and a receptionist who years later would call and exchange greetings cards, even though neither worked at the office any more. They all believed that she did a phenominal job under the circumstances. <br>
<br>
Now, I've talked about my father a lot in these message threads, but have seldom, if ever before talked about my mother. Partly because, being recently deceased he's on my mind, but also out of a sense of protectiveness toward her. <br>
But she was entirely competent in anything she tried; she never felt she had to compete with men. The idea is alien to her; one would as soon compete with an artichoke. It was she who first noticed the male-bashing taking place in the media and brought it to my attention. Make no mistake; she's as disgusted with modern males as she is with modern females. On occassion I'll relate the discussions I get into on the internet, and I'm certain the next messages I post are heavily influenced by her expressed opinions. <br>
<br>
One of the primary philosophies I learned as a youngster can be summed up in an oft heard phrase: &quot;just do what you can do&quot;. Usually this was stated to me as I struggled with a wheelbarrow of mortar that weighed 4 times what I did, or attempted to otherwise do the work of larger and more experienced men. It's easy to see this as a put-down out of context, but what I could do at that time, for example, was spread mortar and hand my father brick; I became good at it. Later he would teach me that spreading mortar is the key to laying brick, and laying them fast. He didn't lay brick because it was fun, or because he could strut around like a bigshot impressing the ladies; he did it because people would give him money for it, and the better he did it, the more money he got, the faster he did it, the farther the money would go. So the bottom line became to do what was necessary to get the brick in the wall fast and well. And that's what &quot;just do what you can do&quot; means. F uck ego. Get the job done. <br>
I've seen and heard so many examples of females being more interested in the ego boost and attention rather than getting the job done that it's embittered me in that regard. One example, specific to construction: a gal is working as a laborer on a commercial jobsite (because they had to hire her...) Her job today is to shovel mortar from the wheelbarrow onto the boards, and to move brick down the scaffold. Except, Ms ego has to be equal; when the other laborers line up to refill their wheelbarrows at the mixer, she gets in line too. Meanwhile the boards get empty. After shooing her back to work 2 or 3 times, they fill her wheelbarrow (actually about 3/4 full), she takes two steps pushing it, and it falls over, taking her with it, wasting the mortar in the barrow, and requiring another batch to be made. This costs time and it costs money. For her ego. She was doing a useful and productive job, but had to do what the boys were doing.<br>
I don't suppose now would be a good time to go into the physiological differences in men and women which explain why a male can lift a wheelbarrow more easily than a female, and why a female can put her head against the wall and lift a chair while a male can't?<br>
I put this in bold so it's sure to be seen...<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  this egoboo attitude drives me nuts with some males as well as females</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> but the current argument is over females.<br>
The society that fosters this nonsense also aggrevates me. Another anecdote: a female walks up to the job site, her eyes casting around... shortly after an OSHA visit in which the inspector had his ears pinned back... her boots are new, her pants clean... she wants a job as a laborer. My brother, without hesitating, says, &quot;Sure, but you have work the same as everyone else.&quot; He then picked up two (85lb?) 12-inch block and set them on the 6 ft scaffold in front of him... just as all the other laborers were doing. She steps between two block... tries to lift... stands up and walks off. It's sometime later confirmed that she was sent out as a test of our hiring practices. <br>
So I don't have any animosity toward women who do what they can do, or do what they have to do, but I have a helluva lot of animosity for females who a) blame men for their situation and/or b) elevate the schoolyard &quot;girls can do what boys can do&quot; to a status of civil rights. <br>
Females are not built like males, they don't think like males, they have different wants, needs, values and priorities than males.  Creating a society that accounts for these differences yet still allows everyone to achieve his or her potential isn't done by changing words from &quot;chairman&quot; to &quot;chairperson&quot; or making sure females and males can be equally irresponsible, stupid, and miserable.<br>
<br>
Suggesting that an enchanter shouldn't fight a hill giant like a warrior doesn't mean that enchanters can't or shouldn't fight hill giants, or that they aren't equal to warriors. Nor is it blasphemy to suggest that maybe that enchanter should kite spectres in oasis (something the warrior can't do, at least not easily and certainly not worth the cost and time) rather than tanking hill giants in Rathe Mtns. And that's the best EQ analogy I can give.<br>
Sure, I get angry in these arguments. I also get angry when someone comes up to me, breathes in my face and shouts, &quot;Blue is 165 miles per hour!&quot; or &quot;Hotdogs shrink leather chariot races!&quot;  That's just my natural reaction to nonsense, no matter how fervently believed.<br>
